.

Gratitude at Christmas: I was thinking today about the legacy of the people who have contributed to my love for art and my willingness to commit to being an artist. 
.
It takes more than a dream, it takes courage to set out on this path, and I wouldn't have had the courage were not for the support and love of so many people in my life, and their creative examples. 
.
This hand stitched cathedral window ornament was made by my aunt Ruth. She made one for each member of my family and mailed them to us every year when we lived in Papua New Guinea. 
.
30 years later. I'm still hanging it on my tree, a memory of Christmases past and hands moving in thoughtful love for family. 
.
I think we far underestimate the value and significance of the acts of love held in creative work. My name is on this ornament, and each stitch signifies an intention and prayer for the recipient. I can't but think that still matters and impacts me today.

I found this in my facebook memories this week. 13 years ago, I had the opportunity to have my art critiqued by a professional artist. I brought three paintings, hungry for feedback on how I could grow as an artist. Maybe I could finally know whether I was kidding myself, trying to establish a career as an artist.
But I couldn't get a babysitter, and despite preparing snacks and quiet games, the kids got antsy and we had to leave before it came my turn for the critique. I felt ashamed and furious and frustrated. Like maybe I was kidding myself even trying to pursue an art career. Maybe the best I could do is make art as a hobby, and squash my dreams for more. 

But I didn't know that I was one year away from making a major shift in my artistic style.

And 2 years away from posting my first video on YouTube.

And 3 years away from launching my first online watercolor course.

First steps that would open the door to an art career that was bigger and better than I could have even imagined. 

I don't know what this means for you and where you're at. I do know that I need to look back at this reminder because even today I get anxious about the future. How am I going to achieve my dreams and goals, especially when there are so many distractions and interruptions? Even though my children are older now, parenting still demands a lot of my time and energy. 

But I do not regret leaving the critique that day, and the lesson it taught me. Because I believe that if you invest in the people you love, even sometimes if it means setting aside your own dreams and goals, what you give will come back to you. And better than you imagined. And more valuable and precious for the waiting. 

There will be a time when what is given in love comes back to you.

One of my favorite intuitive painting exercises is to scatter graphite powder across my painting surface as a first step, and then look for what I can see in the dropped powder. Usually, if I've been working a subject theme, I can use what has fallen on the page to pull another version of that same subject. 

In this painting, I had been working on depicting a street scene from Montreal, and was feeling a little frustrated with my progress. This version appeared in a warm-up and felt like everything I had been trying to do in all the intentional versions prior. I love the way my eye can become trained to see possibilities and even the most random scatter of shape.

There are four paintings that emerged from graphite powder exercises on my gallery page on my website right now. Can you find them all? 
.

There's a little story with this painting. That black line you see an inch or two from the bottom? I had actually placed tape in that area so I could paint a small square landscape on the top of the piece of paper. But as I was painting, I kept pulling color down past the tape so that when I peeled the tape away I had a square landscape at top, a gap, and then a little narrow wide landscape in that extra inch at the bottom. And I liked it! So I added a little bit of color to the space where the tape had been to make it a single painting.
.
I've entered this painting in several competitions and it has been rejected soundly every time. It doesn't follow all the rules of painting design and composition, and maybe that little strip at the bottom confuses people. I don't know, I just know that I like it. Confusing or not, Good design or not, it makes me happy. And that makes it good art. Because the satisfaction of the artist who made it has to be priority number one. I believe it's the artist's inner vision that sparks new art movements and innovation in creativity. And art becomes dangerously repetitive when? "Does it follow the rules of composition" or "what does everyone else think" becomes a foremost goal.
.
I have to remind myself of this when my art is rejected. I never made it to win an award anyway. It's winning in my studio because it makes me smile.
.
#watercolour
#artistproblems #rejection #artmindset

I believe that in watercolor, a beautiful process creates beautiful paintings, and I try to start every painting session by reminding myself of that.
.
In a world where far too often we are told we need to work harder, do better, show up more flawlessly, it's even more important to develop a creative practice that allows you to be... Just be.
.
Be yourself.
.
Be present.
.
Be okay with whatever you are able to bring right now.
.
Doesn't that idea make you breathe a little easier? I feel my shoulders relax just typing those three sentences. 
.
Whatever you have today, it's enough.
. 
Watercolor can be your happy place, your place of freedom and meditative presence and joy. But that doesn't mean you don't have to fight for it!
.
In a world full of not enoughness, regaining that equilibrium of presence and peace is one of the hardest battles. I am so thankful for the courageous artists who have mentored me, and my hope is that this week's 2 days of watercolor inspiration will free other artists to be who they are meant to be.
Watercolor Bootcamp is a tongue in cheek name for an event that's far more than a painting workout. Come and join us! There's space for you at the easel.

Isn't this such a beautiful space? I love my painting studio, and I do feel a little like the exception to the rule, to be an artist to have such a beautiful place to work in. 
.
When I started painting, I painted first on the sofa in our little rental house and I kept all my painting stuff in a bag beside the couch. 
.
And when the kids were little, we had a big great room where they could play and make their own messes, and my painting stuff was spread out on a table in that big room. And sometimes yes, they did stick their fingers in my palette. 
.
And for a lot of years my studio space was an empty shell, waiting for us to have the time and money to finish it. And then, there were the arguments about how to finish it, how to make the space usable, should we rent it out, should we try to make it multi-purpose or could I justify dedicating the whole space to art.
. 
I am so glad that we took the time to do it right, and for my husband's amazing eye in design and construction follow through. He is a carpenter who loves his work, and the studio space was a labour of love.
.
I'm thankful that I didn't need an amazing space to be able to learn watercolor. I wanted it badly enough that I was going to paint no matter what. And that's not only the key to becoming an artist, it's a key to developing skill and learning technique, no matter what your obstacles are. 
.
I always hope that when I'm teaching, that's the message I'm communicating. Whatever you have to give to your art, it's enough. Show up with that. Be thankful, even if you're crammed on the couch with your painting stuff on your lap. We get to paint!
.
#mindfulstudio #artstudio #atelier #studiotour

What do you see when you look at a tree? Last night I was sitting with friends and I started talking about how I feel called to look up. To take my eyes off my feet and my problems and expand my viewpoint outward.
.
 That shift in perspective gives me the ability to see what is happening beyond the limited scope of my own self-focus.
.
 And it sparked a discussion so quickly!
.
 Everyone in the room understood how easily we slip into an inward gaze that misses the big picture. 
.
Someone else started talking about lying on the ground and looking up through the trees, how every tree is reaching up towards the sky. And our imaginations were captured by the metaphor. So painting trees is powerful.
.

This week I taught two watercolor workshops on Zoom, sharing different variations of one reference photo. I'm always amazed at how much I get out of one scene when I give myself permission to paint it multiple times, try different ways of expressing myself and ask a new questions with each version. 
.
If you're new to painting, you can put a lot of emotional energy into one painting, and it might feel overwhelming to think about painting something more than once. The good news is, that emotional energy becomes less taxing when you give yourself permission to breathe into the process and pace yourself, rather than trying to get it perfect the first time. 
.
I'm looking forward to doing more of these live stream workshops next month ! Want to join me?

Earlier in February, I taught two online painting workshops featuring this beautiful tree at the edge of a creek. My process of developing any new scene is one of repeatedly painting the subject. I love seeing how many possibilities can be discovered in one painting, and learning how to edit out the non-essential elements.
.
I remember being really resistant to the idea of repeating a painting when I was new painter. Every version took so much emotional energy that I couldn't imagine starting over. But now, seeing how much change and discovery is possible even in the course of a single week, it's both fun and freeing to work in this method.
.

When I think about teaching watercolor travel workshops, I think about this photo from Italy 2021 and the joy in my eyes here. That's the look of a dream come true. 

I used to read the ads for travel workshops in the back of watercolour magazines and imagine another life where such things were possible for me. Even though I have always prioritized making art, it has taken me a long time to realize that I can ask for good things and name my dreams out loud. 

I can't imagine how I would have responded if someone had told me that one day I'd be teaching watercolour internationally and experiencing the world through my artist's eyes. It's a wonderful gift and I am so thankful.

This year I am looking forward to teaching in Vancouver Island in April, Madeline Island Wisconsin in July, and Cornwall England in September. Every new place is a thrill to discover, I always want to see the world with wonder.

Good relationships are only possible if there's trust. In art this has multiple layers; I want to trust my tools - the medium itself to be engaged in creating something beautiful, but I also need to trust myself - that I have good instincts and responses to participate in making this process beautiful and meaningful. And those exercises in trust have given me so much! 
.

I almost lost this painting when I tried to mount it on a wood panel last week. I love mounting watercolor on wood, the treatment gives me the opportunity to display it without glass, but If it goes badly, the painting is ruined. (If you'd like a tutorial, you can look it up on my YouTube channel)
I'm so glad this painting survived because it's been many years in development. From the first time I tried working with graphite powder, to my explorations with using stencils to create texture in watercolor and the continual challenge to be bolder and braver in my painting process, I have been learning and building knowledge, and working to open my heart to new possibilities. The actual painting process itself took time, as I created an underpainting, built up color, removed color and pushed forward through several times when I thought maybe I'd gone too far and overworked the painting. 
.
I dropped this painting off at the art gallery this afternoon and it will be hanging with the @peace_river_chapter_fca winter show for the next few weeks at the @dawsoncreekartgallery 
.
I'm beginning to think my art journey is simply a process of learning to be braver and to live beyond my fear.
.

There are certain seasons of the year where I can easily feel like I'm getting behind or missing out. When another artist is sharing about what they've learned recently, how they are leveling up in growth in their medium, and maybe I'm feeling a little stalled. When my art is rejected from an exhibit or publication, and others seem to be getting career recognition. When I just haven't had the time to invest in my art during a season where family commitments take priority. 
.
Despite that feeling of not being able to keep up, I try to remind myself that my art is intrinsically part of my identity. Just as my personal growth is something that happens imperceptibly over time, even when I am not actively studying, I am growing as an artist.
.
There is always going to be a feeling of scarcity in some aspect of my art journey. Whether the challenge is time, location, or simply my brain's capacity to take in new information and my body's ability to implement it, I can look back and see the sheer volume of what I have learned over the last several decades of pursuing artistic expression, and trust that what I know today is enough, and that I am continuing to learn to strengthen my art for the future.
.
Trust is the keyword, I think. With an attitude of trust, I can be more present in my art practice, and I need that if I'm going to paint with anything resembling authenticity.

I have never thought of myself as an academic painter. Break out the charts and terminology and I shudder. Painting is play for me, but play is learning too! So over the decades, I have been able to learn about colour, design, technique etc simply by experimenting and trying things. So when I whipped out these little charts today to help my students during tomorrow's Zoom workshop, I was a little startled about the volume of knowledge that poured out.
.
I think we have such a tension between work and play, wanting to be productive and "good." I am thankful that play doesn't require anything, and yet in a sense it requires everything. 
.
"Playing is an act of faith." - Katie Bowser Hutson
.
#watercolour #intuitivewatercolor #selftaughtartist

My studio is full of little found objects; feathers, rocks, nests and bark. Special treasures to connect me to environment and the things I love to discover.
.
It's tempting as an artist to feel like the more complex a painting the better it is, but it's contrary to the joy I feel witnessing a little glimpse of simple beauty, fixing my eyes on color and pattern in tree bark, or the sheen of color on a feather. Maybe complex works for some artists, but I am always trying to get closer to the heart, core principles, deep values, simple truths.
.
There is freedom in fixing my focus on one thing and letting everything else go for a little while. I think this can apply to a painting subject, but even more so to an entire creative practice, and perhaps even a life well lived.

Image text: Ways to grow your art when you're not painting.
1. Discover new artists. Study contemporary and past artists with the goal of expanding your palate.
2. Look for the light. Pause a notice how the light falls on a scene, colors cast and patterns created.
3. Speak a painting. Describe to yourself the steps you would take to depict what you're seeing.

Can you see how this painting might have been inspired by the same subject that inspired my last post? While this version might seem more simplistic, it actually took quite a bit longer to paint. I stopped often to study what was in front of me on paper and think about whether I felt composition to be working. (See photos 6,7,8)

There is no 100% objective analysis of a composition. When artists talk about studying design and making design very important in their paintings, I think it's important to remember that design isn't arbitrary. Despite all of the composition, diagrams and overlays that could be applied to evaluating a piece of artwork, what you see is always going to be informed by what you know and how you feel. Your personal taste, your body of knowledge, you bring that with you when you judge art, whether it's your art or someone else's.
.
I want my compositions to be strong, I want my paintings to have connection and flow and I'm always working to grow stronger in this area. But it's not really a topic you can nail down and sometimes critics or jurors will disagree. What might seem to be a design flaw could also be the most effective part of the painting. 
.
I believe in taking feedback. And I also believe in growing technically. But I also love knowing that I can work outside creative norms or standards of design.

I'm taking a landscape painting course for the next couple of weeks. It might be easy to think that a professional artist doesn't need to invest in learning from other artists, but I actually think that what a professional artist does that is different from novices is that we don't avoid addressing our weak areas.
 .
As a young painter, I felt like my weak areas were a condemnation of my identity as an artist. I was learning from others but more in a mindset of avoiding the work of looking at what my art was missing and focusing my time there. I felt defeated by my weaknesses.
.
Now I have come to know that there are no shortcuts or quick fixes, but if I look at where I need to grow and focus time there, it will work and I will strengthen my art! That's a good reason to face what I'm struggling with and make time to experiment, try new approaches with the goal of seeing new growth. 
.
This painting took 2 years from the initial conception because when I started, I didn't have the skill to pull my vision together yet. I worked on it for a time, then put it away and kept painting. A year later I tried again and it worked! Incubating the project helped me develop strategies that created a painting that worked.

Bad photos can make a great start for a painting! I Love taking photos and I often have great ones in my camera roll, but it's usually the crappy photos that I choose to paint. And I think this is because a calendar worthy photo can make me feel limited to trying to copy the beauty that is already there. If my photo is blurry, or drab in some way, it can actually create more opportunities for me to draw out the beauty in that photo. 
.
You want to be careful about this because not all bad photos make good paintings. Some simply have too much detail, poorly placed shapes and elements that might be hard to figure out how to edit. Sometimes a poor photo doesn't have enough information and you need to spend a lot of time filling in the missing pieces. Sometimes there are competing dominant shapes and you might struggle to figure out how to paint something that can be journeyed through in a not confusing way. A lot like that sentence.
.
But when a drab or blurry photo has good lines and shapes, it can be so much fun to draw out the beauty and play with using it as a foundation for something truly original. Remember also that working with your own photos means you get to bring memory and vision to the scene that is authentic and adds life to something that might have felt lifeless under the camera's gaze.
.

When you walk away and let a painting dry, the last thing you want is to come back and find out there's a big ugly hard edge right in the wrong spot. I used to find big water marks just a few inches in from the edge of my paper, especially along the corners, or a bloom that had appeared in the middle of a painting that I left to dry. 
.
One of my habits now is to take a moment to wipe the edges of my paper before I walk away. Usually I do it twice, pausing for about 30 seconds in between. At a slight angle so that no water pools in the middle of the page. If I'm going to get a pool or a bead of water, I want it to be along the edge. 
.
I also periodically wipe the edges of my paper during the painting process, not just when I walk away. It's so easy for those beads of water to collect at the edges and slow the drying time in those spaces. 
.
I like blooms and I often create them deliberately, but if you're a novice painter and are finding watery puddles collecting at the edges or in the buckles of your paper, often just monitoring the angle of your paper and blotting those pools is a good place to start.
.

When I look back at my art journey, I see two distinct phases of development, separated by a pivot point when I realized that everything was going to change from here on out. I didn't know what my heart-led authentic style was going to look like for me, but I knew I had to start out on that path.
.
Here are 10 “rules” I’ve learned about the heart-led artistic journey. These are the principles that guide me as I continually find that there is more freedom, joy and beauty ahead for me and my art.

1. Success comes from what you do consistently
2. Diversity invites expansion
3. Growth will only be recognized in hindsight
4. Growth from inside the situation feels like discomfort
5. It’s okay to break things
6. Avoid words like mistake, fail, finished, success, perfect
7. "Can’t" usually conceals a limiting perception
8. You don’t get to be certain
9. Listen to experts but Trust yourself
10. Even when you’re not painting, you’re painting.

 I'm curious; do these resonate for you? What do these short phrases prompt as you think about your own creative process? I'd love to hear about it, leave a comment!

How wet is too wet in watercolour? I'll answer this like I answer every student question; it depends! Every stage has a different kind of responsiveness to your brush and the moisture and paint on your brush. The more you paint, the easier it will be to anticipate what is going to happen when that wet brush touches the paper. And that's the best argument I have for why the best painters are the ones who are too stubborn to quit.
.
What stage of flow in your painting is your favorite? Lately, I've been really loving that near dry stage when I can create some very soft blended brush strokes. It's funny because it's also the stage where I'm most likely to make a mistake. 
.

I have a legacy of loving, strong, hard-working and generous mothers to thank today. In my upbringing, creativity has always been paired with resourcefulness; my grandmothers came from large families without a lot of time for anything but work but they always looked for ways to make their homes and lives more beautiful. Scrap quilts, a touch of paint, and flowers.
My first memories are of the "new quilt spread;" one person ready with the camera while a quilt fresh off the quilt frame was unfurled by two others for its first presentation in completion. We have family photo albums just dedicated to quilts.
.
And tables, spread with handmade goods at the country fair, red and blue ribbons representing the work of our family's hands. The competition for best buns was fierce and I yearned to be old enough to participate. When I bake now, I use family recipes that have never been equalled.
Instagram isn't really the place for this kind of reminiscing, the memories are rolling in faster and faster. Today I'm going to pull out some old albums and spend some time back on the farm.

It's one of my favourite local views and I can remember imagining a road leading up into the sky as a child. Expansive spaces load the imagination!

Enrollment is now open for two new live online sky workshops in watercolor, taking place May 29th and 31st on Zoom. I have been so excited about these two workshops as I've played with skies these last few weeks. There is a wonderful canvas for the imagination right over our heads and exploring edges, light and shadow and color is going to sharpen your skills in painting other subjects as well. 
.
As I've played with skies this time around, I realized that I've been holding back a little bit when I've painted skies in the past and this is a place for experimentation, exaggeration and playful techniques that feel unexpected. I started adding line where I used to keep everything very soft, and that felt exciting. Pushing my boundaries has rarely been something I've regretted, even when I took the painting too far and it didn't turn out, I gained so much more than when I play it safe.

Have You ever been in a situation where you felt like things weren't going to work out, and it made you feel like you had reached too far and been too audacious or ambitious in your goals?
.
Recently I took captive a thought pattern that had me feeling frustrated and stuck. I had started looking at a situation as though I was a victim rather than someone who had options and choices. And I think this is a common instinct for us!
.
It felt very freeing and exciting to realize that a situation that I had been feeling powerless about was actually a place for opportunity and some options I hadn't considered. Rather than feeling shame and failure, I pushed myself to try some new things, and that way, even if the situation didn't work out, I could still know at least that it wasn't because I hadn't given it everything I had.
.
Life lessons are art lessons and vice versa, and this situation often happens in smaller ways during a painting, and in larger ways when I think about my art career. I always want to guard against this victim mindset!
.
And by the way, if you've been feeling like you're one of the people meant to learn and grow with me on Madeline island, there are a few seats available and I can give you info if you send me a message.

Last week I photographed 60 paintings! I guess it's very clear where my procrastination really flourishes. 
.
Looking through past paintings is always a practice of reliving an experience. And, in a sense, I'm telling stories back to myself of the things that I love and what captivates my attention.
.
And maybe if we think of art as a practice of soul care, there's something very beautiful about that process of review and remembrance. I want to nurture that part of myself that looks for beauty, that lingers over texture, colour, shape.

Personal artistic development to me, means pushing a subject and seeing how far I can take it. I like the idea of stretching the subject like rubber, although I think I'm probably pretty timid in the way I approach this process, I also believe that I'm teaching myself to be braver.
.
So as I've explored skies this month, my goal has not just been to teach the subject in my online zoom workshops, but it's to strengthen my own skills, expand my boundaries of what I'm capable of, and I've really seen that pay off, even though I've only been exploring it for a few weeks.
.
Sometimes we think growth will only be measured in long spans of time, but this kind of single subject focus can reap big games and new ideas really quickly, especially if it's a subject you think you know well and how exciting it is to find a new level to take it to.
.

I ran across this quote from artist Corey Hardeman this morning and It struck a chord with me because this is exactly the kind of perspective I want to continue to cultivate in my own art practice. 
.
I think sometimes people are confused by the fact that I sell very few paintings and I put very little effort into selling paintings, and I haven't been able to articulate why I don't invest more energy into selling art. 
.
Imposter syndrome is a factor, but it's not the only factor. Certainly there is a special kind of rejection in putting paintings up for sale and not selling any, but this isn't a crippling fear for me. When a painting is finished, my first instinct isn't, "How can I get this into the world and out of the studio," but, "What will this painting bring to the next painting?" I immediately want to move on paint further out of what I've been learning and exploring.
.

The birds always sound incredible, but I had installed the Merlin app and it lets you record bird song and then it identifies the birds. Amazingly, the app captured over 20 varieties of birds, mostly small sparrow type songbirds and warblers. I wasn't sure if I should trust its accuracy, but on the return journey, it picked up the same birds in the same places. Swipe for drama! This was a first for me, teaching a class where I actually drew out a vanishing point and perspective was a strong focus. 
.
I think it's interesting that so many art classes emphasize learning perspective as a foundational skill when I have spent most of my art career avoiding it. I have instead tried to base my paintings on good observation (even if you don't know how perspective works, good observation will take you far) and on intuition, allowing expression, shape, colour, energy to be prioritized. 
.
The first version of the scene was carefully painted following perspective guidelines, and the second is a version where the guidelines have been internalized and offer only the loosest framework for the rest of the painting. Which do you prefer?

Please, artists, stop hating on your own work! As I looked at this painting to upload it to social media, I was tempted to choose something else. There are a few brush strokes I'm not 100% thrilled with and it's easy to let my eyes fix on them instead of enjoying the marvelous energy and dynamic marks in the whole painting.
.
We like to call ourselves perfectionists or see that we demand a high standard, but in obsessing over tiny imperfections we are also limiting the scope of what we feel free to create. And I think over time the result is either work that is consistent but uninspired, or an accumulation of discouragement because your paintings so rarely meet your standards. 
.
There are a few marks I don't love in this painting, but there are so many more that I am completely delighted with and that's what I'm choosing to focus on. I'm dancing in the rain but that means I am willing to get a little wet.

I titled this painting "Be Seen" because I think it is easier to hide. Especially if an artist has a degree of skill in technique, that can become an armor to protect you from criticism or being misunderstood. 
.
In choosing to paint in a more open-ended way, this painting evolved out of a simplicity of one movement following the next and each one informing what was to come in a very instinctive way, this opens up a lot of vulnerability.
.
With an approach like this, the statement is, "here I am, do you see me?" Which means it feels very personal and there's very little to hide behind.
.
The more I choose to paint in this kind of vulnerability and freedom, the more it feels kind of rebellious. I live in an environment where realism and refined technique is the accepted standard of excellence, so to deliberately choose an alternative route is to push back, to demand to be seen for more than my technique. And it's really important to me that I could be allowed to do that. It's important to me that you be allowed to do that too.

I spent a lot of time in the early years of making art waiting for validation. I really wanted someone to tell me my art was good...and not just a family member! It was funny how, when praise did start coming in, it didn't seem to help me feel confident about my art.

It wasn't until I started setting my own criteria for judging my art that I felt like I could stand by my work with confidence. And suddenly, other people's criticism had less weight, or maybe, the right kind of weight. 
.
We can be devastated by criticism, and yet brush off praise. 
We can receive feedback from someone who knows nothing about what we are trying to achieve, and then place so much weight on trying to please them that we lose sight of who we are. 
Learning how to evaluate your work based on YOUR own goals and inner sense of what resonates is critical to your thriving as an individual artist! And that's what today's #worldwatercolormonth video is about. Watch it by clicking the link in my profile.

"It doesn't matter what you planned to do, what matters is what you find yourself doing." I heard this quote on the Habit podcast from Jonathan Rogers and I've been thinking about how it relates to art.
.
I started painting with an idea in mind, but the painting quickly becomes something else. The biggest mistake I can make is to be overly committed to my first idea and allow that to limit my choices and actions in the context of the painting.
.
I teach watercolor, but I don't want to teach people how to do it right. Because who can know? Our first idea of what is right for the painting is never how the painting will become. I cannot trust myself to have infallible vision for my art. The " integrity of my process" (boy, I love that phrase!) Is one that can only be discovered in an environment of curiosity and non-judgment, vulnerability and trust.

There's no getting around the fact that if you want to sell art or build an art career, you need to know how to market your work. There are very few artists who are able to outsource their marketing to an agent or a gallery. If you're not in that stratosphere, you can still have a thriving art career and you can develop marketing skills that don't feel sleazy or systemized. 
.
I think it's funny that art is so personal and creative, and takes forms that are surprising and non-linear and yet when it comes to marketing we are supposed to suddenly adopt systems and structures that don't feel natural to the creative process! I don't think it has to be this way!
.
Just as your art is created out of an environment of your personal values and interests and weird obsessions, your marketing can take the same direction and reflect who you are. That's one thing that's really wonderful about taking business online.

It's interesting what happens when you let go of the impulse to justify or describe a painting. If I am rightly prioritizing the process rather than the outcome, it's a logical transition to move toward letting go of any imposition of outcome on my painting.
. 
In practical terms, what this looks like is not choosing a reference photo or a subject. It means trusting that my intuitive reactions during process will inform the painting better than chosen directions will. Maybe I carry inside myself something more than the reference photo is allowing me to show.
.
Yesterday I worked on the piece I'm showing here and just tried to really engage with what I saw on the paper. And the textures here are just so beautiful. 
.
I think letting go of outcome to trust the process and letting myself be as fully informed by intuitive response as possible is kind of a statement on existence. To live today with presence, yes, moving in a direction toward the better world and growth I dream of, but in the living to also make space to honour the only time that's guaranteed: now.

Most of my artistic battles don't happen on the paper. I've learned that I need to be very aware of what my thoughts are telling me if I want to make art with the courage and confidence I want to see in my work. 
.

Before and after. I think much of my art practice is teaching myself to be more audacious. 

I never thought I would be this audacious about my art. It's a surprise and a delight that I am making paintings now and thinking, "I don't think I care whether this fits any artistic rubric or not. Societal or artistic standards are the very thing I'm fighting to be free of, and my opinion and fulfillment in the work is my artist's statement." 
I never knew it mattered to me to color outside of those lines, and I'm amazed at myself that I am becoming strong enough to live in that way. It is the principles I've adopted for my art practice that are teaching me how to live like this, and I'm so grateful and inspired.

How about you?

Sometimes I tend to think about composition as an external thing; a set of guidelines that I need to remember and then grade my painting on. But from today, I'm choosing to reject that thinking and simply evaluate my work based on what I know and the information I will be continuing to add to my knowledge.
.
Because the truth is, design has never been as simple as, does this painting fit the rubric? And we need to stop acting like it is.

There was a time when my future as an artist seemed unnavigable and impossible to penetrate. There were so many obstacles I faced and finding a path that allowed me to make the art I'd always dreamed seemed impossible.⁠

And I can't help but wonder if maybe the art journey is meant to have these obstacles. Maybe they are the actual building blocks to teach you how to be the artist you were meant to be. ⁠
⁠
Think about it; no one's art journey thrives when we are busy doing what we're told. You want more from your art than to copy what others are doing. You are meant to make art that reflects who you are, but maybe you have been waiting for someone to validate what that is. You hate the art you're making that feels so stifled and rigid but you can't seem to find a way to make it your own.⁠
⁠
Imagine with me that you get to be the pathfinder, blazing a trail that will lead you to the art your heart truly wants to make. What kind of process creates the results you need to find your artistic voice and freedom?⁠
⁠
I'm going to give you some homework today. Take five minutes and think about the obstacles that make you think, "If only..." What have you been thinking of as an obstacle that is holding you back? What if you changed your perspective? ⁠

"Man, I love this." Do you feel that way about your art? For me, it started out with a single brush stroke, a tiny portion of a painting that looked like, just maybe, a real artist had painted it. 
.
I had to teach myself how to identify what was valuable and worth keeping in my own paintings and it wasn't always easy or natural. 
.
Sometimes the parts of the painting I was most critical of would reveal themselves to be full of secret beauty. I had to learn to be less judgmental of my first impressions so I didn't give up on a painting just because at first it seemed like a failure.
.
I had to make peace with the fact that other people wouldn't always see what I saw. And maybe my most inspired work would take time for others to develop a taste for.
.
The thing is, when you're deeply satisfied in your own work and convinced that it is the best and most authentic thing you have to offer, it becomes much easier to stand by it and find joy in it, even when it's not successful by measurable standards. 
.
And when art is created that nourishes your own heart, the healing it provides is more valuable than any dollar figure. Art becomes a way of enriching life, your view of the world, your hope in the future, and the generosity and grace you are able to offer to others. 
.
That has been my experience. It's an experience I'm passionate about sharing. 
.

When I'm working on my art, I try to be very careful of my language. Oh, I'm not cursing a blue streak, but there are thoughts and phrases that are destructive to my creative flow and process. ⁠
Two key indicators that my mindset is verging on dangerous territory are when I start thinking in statements, instead of questions. ⁠
"This is terrible."⁠
"If only I had more resources..."⁠
"When I master this skill, I will be happy with my work."⁠
"I can't believe I made the same mistake again!" ⁠
⁠
Statement phrases are so limiting, aren't they? These words stop me in my tracks. They don't offer anything but judgment. ⁠
⁠
Questions, on the other hand, are thrilling and expansive. They help me move forward with anticipation and hope. Try answering your statements with "what if" questions. ⁠
"What if I tried something new?"⁠
"What if that mistake could become a star feature of the painting?"⁠
"What if I can use this problem and become a stronger painter through what it teaches me?"⁠
⁠

Another experiment in the photo- transfer-to-watercolour adventure! The trees were a laser print from a photo, transferred to watercolor paper with prodigious use of paint thinner ( lacquer thinner is supposed to be more effective) and pressure; rubbing really hard to transfer the image from one piece of paper to another.

I got a soft ghostly image, but it took a lot of work and time and some pretty toxic solvents. So I'm not sure that I would recommend this process. I also don't like that the paint thinners saturated the watercolor paper and the odor was pretty strong even after the chemicals were put away. I can use these to help me set achievable goals for the year ahead as well.

What I know about art is...not what I expected when I started. It's so much better.

Truthfully I'm already tired of thinking about goals for 2024. Wouldn't it be nice to just ease into 2024 and continue to settle into a lifelong artistic practice instead of some kind of push to fix what feels broken, be more disciplined, and achieve more? 
.
I used to think that I would feel better about my art if I made more successful paintings, but it turned out to be the reverse. I learned how to create a healthier mindset in my art practice and that made my paintings come to life. So if I can dedicate this year to a richer experience of being present in my art practice, I can trust that the rest of it - the art I'm meant to make with joy this year - will come together. I think this is the key to a lifelong, deeply enriching artistic practice. Let's commit to that together in 2024!

This is the other yupo painting I did over New Year's. This one offered an experiment in mark making, but in the end I struggled with the passage of connecting colors down the center of the page. 
.
Yupo is pretty forgiving so I was able to try a couple of different strategies, using a lot of black to add a dark passage, wiping that away and then finally ending up with a white ink. 
.
Came back to the painting after it had dried and the white ink had cracked and flaked, which you can see in the second and third images. I never call an outcome like this a mistake, because maybe that texture can bring something to the painting even if my first reaction is "oh no, that shouldn't have happened." 
.
What this painting offers, even with a troubling central passage, is the problem solving and technique development that happen when you're working with a new process. And my second yupo painting offered the opportunity to implement what I learned from the first and continue the development process.
If you're only defining a painting by whether it turned out or not, you're failing to recognize all of the ways your process will benefit your future work.
